children.text: The polyethylene vapour barrier beneath the slab has not been installed to allow it to be turned up the external side faces of its edge beams continually around this home’s floor slab, which will allow moisture ingress via slab edge dampness into the internal timber wall skins and/or the floor coverings.
It is a requirement of Part 3.2.2.6 Vapour Barriers of the NCC/BCA that

‘The vapour barrier must be placed beneath the slab so that the bottom surface of the slab is entirely underlaid and extends under edge beams to finish at ground level in accordance with Figure 3.2.2.3’
Additionally, the relevant Australian Standard AS 2870 Slab & Footing Construction, clause 5.3.3 Vapour Barriers and Damp-proofing Membranes states that
‘Vapour barriers shall be installed so that the bottom surface of the slab and beams, including internal beams, is entirely underlaid. The membrane shall extend under the edge beam to ground level’ .
The vapour barrier should be properly extended, lapped and sealed to ensure it can be turned up the slab edges prior to concrete being poured.
